  "text": "# GCC Stack Clash Protection Implementation Audit\n\n## Overview\nStack clash protection is a security feature in GCC designed to mitigate stack-clash attacks by inserting probes that detect stack allocation attempts and prevent attackers from jumping over the guard page. The implementation spans multiple files across the GCC codebase.\n\n## Key Implementation Files\n\n### 1. X86_64 Stack Clash Probing (gcc/config/i386/i386.cc)\nThe x86_64 target implements stack clash protection through the `ix86_adjust_stack_and_probe()` function (defined at line 8215). This function handles stack allocation with embedded probing for the x86_64 architecture. The implementation checks `flag_stack_clash_protection` to determine if probing should be enabled and uses probe intervals defined by `param_stack_clash_protection_probe_interval`. The function is called from within the function prologue/epilogue generation when `flag_stack_clash_protection` is set (line 9491-9494).\n\n### 2. Generic Stack Clash Expansion (gcc/explow.cc)\nThe generic stack clash protection expansion is implemented through multiple functions:\n- `anti_adjust_stack_and_probe_stack_clash()` (line 2072): The primary function for stack clash protection that allocates stack space while probing to prevent clash attacks\n- `anti_adjust_stack_and_probe()` (line 2201): The traditional stack checking probe function (different from stack clash protection)\n- `compute_stack_clash_protection_loop_data()` (line 1955): Computes the loop parameters for stack probing\n- `emit_stack_clash_protection_probe_loop_start()` (line 2014): Emits RTL for starting the probe loop\n- `emit_stack_clash_protection_probe_loop_end()` (line 2036): Emits RTL for ending the probe loop\n\nThese functions work together to emit probing code that touches each page of allocated stack space, ensuring the guard page is not jumped over.\n\n### 3. Function Declarations (gcc/explow.h)\nThe header file `gcc/explow.h` declares the stack probing functions:\n- `anti_adjust_stack_and_probe()` at line 74\n- `anti_adjust_stack_and_probe_stack_clash()` at line 78\n\nThese declarations make the functions available to other compilation units.\n\n### 4. Option Definitions\n\n#### gcc/common.opt (line 3054-3057)\nDefines the `-fstack-clash-protection` compiler option as:\n```\nfstack-clash-protection\nCommon Var(flag_stack_clash_protection) Optimization\nInsert code to probe each page of stack space as it is allocated to protect\nfrom stack-clash style attacks.\n```\n\n#### gcc/params.opt (lines 1108-1114)\nDefines tuning parameters:\n- `-param=stack-clash-protection-guard-size=` (line 1109): Size of the stack guard as a power of two (default 12, range 12-30)\n- `-param=stack-clash-protection-probe-interval=` (line 1113): Interval for probing as a power of two (default 12, range 10-16)\n\n### 5. Target Hook Implementation\n\n#### gcc/targhooks.cc and gcc/targhooks.h\nImplement `default_stack_clash_protection_alloca_probe_range()` which provides the default probe range for alloca() calls. Individual targets can override this hook.\n\n#### Target-Specific Implementations\n- `gcc/config/aarch64/aarch64.cc`: Defines `aarch64_stack_clash_protection_alloca_probe_range()` (line 33925-33926)\n- `gcc/config/riscv/riscv.cc`: Defines `riscv_stack_clash_protection_alloca_probe_range()`\n\n### 6. Test Suite\n\n#### gcc/testsuite/gcc.target/i386/stack-clash-protection.c\nThe primary test file for x86_64 stack clash protection validation. It tests compilation with `-O2 -fstack-clash-protection` flags.\n\nAdditional stack clash tests exist for other targets:\n- AArch64: `gcc/testsuite/gcc.target/aarch64/sve/pcs/stack_clash_*.c`\n- S390: `gcc/testsuite/gcc.target/s390/stack-clash-*.c`\n\n## Implementation Chain\n\nThe stack clash protection works through the following call chain:\n\n1. **Option Processing**: `-fstack-clash-protection` flag (gcc/common.opt) sets `flag_stack_clash_protection`\n\n2. **Prologue Generation**: For x86_64 targets, `ix86_adjust_stack_and_probe()` (gcc/config/i386/i386.cc:8215) is called during function prologue generation when stack allocation exceeds the guard size\n\n3. **Generic Expansion**: The generic expansion uses `anti_adjust_stack_and_probe_stack_clash()` (gcc/explow.cc:2072) which calls:\n   - `compute_stack_clash_protection_loop_data()` to determine probe interval\n   - `emit_stack_clash_protection_probe_loop_start()` to emit loop setup RTL\n   - `emit_stack_clash_protection_probe_loop_end()` to emit loop termination RTL\n\n4. **Target Hooks**: The implementation uses `targetm.stack_clash_protection_alloca_probe_range()` which is defined in targhooks.cc with target-specific overrides in architecture files (aarch64.cc, riscv.cc, etc.)\n\n## Security Mechanism\n\nThe stack clash protection works by:\n1. Probing the stack at intervals (typically 4KB/12 = ~4K bytes) when allocating large amounts of stack space\n2. Using guard pages to prevent jumping over the probed region\n3. Ensuring that even with allocations smaller than the probe interval, continuous allocations will eventually hit a probe\n4. Supporting both prologue-based probing (fixed allocations) and runtime probing (variable allocations via alloca())\n"
}

